<i> prisoners who've managed  to escape the camps.</i>

246
00:10:56,688 --> 00:10:59,357
That is truly horrific. But the existence,

247
00:10:59,924 --> 00:11:01,526
the continued existence of those camps

248
00:11:01,626 --> 00:11:03,961
brings us to a really important point to understand.

249
00:11:04,062 --> 00:11:07,231
Kim Jong-un is terrified of losing power.

250
00:11:07,331 --> 00:11:10,235
And while we love to present him as a madman, many experts

251
00:11:10,336 --> 00:11:12,403
believe that his actions are motivated by rational

252
00:11:12,504 --> 00:11:13,504
self-preservation.

253
00:11:13,905 --> 00:11:17,074
He has seen leaders like Saddam Hussein and Muammar Gadhafi

254
00:11:17,274 --> 00:11:20,377
scale back their nuclear programs, only to be overthrown,

255
00:11:20,479 --> 00:11:22,882
either by the U.S., or by their own people,

256
00:11:22,981 --> 00:11:24,182
and die gruesome deaths.

257
00:11:24,383 --> 00:11:26,485
And it's true that dictators generally don't

258
00:11:26,585 --> 00:11:29,588
end their careers like disgraced American politicians,

259
00:11:29,687 --> 00:11:31,723
with a stint on<i>  Dancing with the Stars,</i>

260
00:11:31,823 --> 00:11:34,992
although, that would've been an incredible season.

261
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:39,063
Saddam, that foxtrot was a weapon of mass seduction.

262
00:11:39,163 --> 00:11:41,765
And, Muammar... You worked hard and it showed.

263
00:11:41,865 --> 00:11:43,134
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

264
00:11:43,235 --> 00:11:47,538
So, Kim Jong-un has continued his family's military-first

265
00:11:47,639 --> 00:11:52,211
policy, spending huge amounts of money on what is the fourth largest military on Earth

266
00:11:52,311 --> 00:11:54,213
and an expensive nuclear program

267
00:11:54,312 --> 00:11:57,115
in an impoverished country whose economy has been estimated

268
00:11:57,215 --> 00:12:00,018
to be smaller than that of Birmingham, Alabama.

269
00:12:00,485 --> 00:12:02,620
And Birmingham is a small economy.

270
00:12:02,721 --> 00:12:04,255
Their most notable export

271
00:12:04,355 --> 00:12:06,957
is<i> American Idol</i> season five winner, Taylor Hicks.

272
00:12:07,057 --> 00:12:09,494
Not that I'm saying that's a bad thing.

273
00:12:09,594 --> 00:12:10,696
Soul patrol forever!

274
00:12:10,929 --> 00:12:13,231
Soul patrol 'till I fucking die!

275
00:12:13,798 --> 00:12:18,370
So, how can Kim Jong-un justify that spending?

276
00:12:18,470 --> 00:12:21,406
Well, he argues that the huge military is the only thing

277
00:12:21,505 --> 00:12:24,208
staving off imminent invasion from a host of outsiders

278
00:12:24,308 --> 00:12:26,544
and that is where we come in.

279
00:12:26,879 --> 00:12:29,281
Because the most dominant and useful villain

280
00:12:29,380 --> 00:12:31,382
in North Korea's narrative is the United States.

281
00:12:31,649 --> 00:12:33,918
And it is not like that comes out of nowhere.

282
00:12:34,019 --> 00:12:36,321
We sided with the south during the Korean War.

283
00:12:36,421 --> 00:12:38,456
And while many Americans may have forgotten just

284
00:12:38,557 --> 00:12:39,792
how devastating that war was,

285
00:12:39,892 --> 00:12:42,060
the North Koreans certainly haven't.

286
00:12:42,159 --> 00:12:44,395
They have an entire museum devoted

287
00:12:44,495 --> 00:12:45,663
to American war atrocities.

288
00:12:46,197 --> 00:12:50,067
And I'm not saying there were none, but I don't think any were

289
00:12:50,168 --> 00:12:51,870
quite as over-the-top as this.

290
00:12:52,738 --> 00:12:53,639
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

291
00:12:54,105 --> 00:12:56,375
REPORTER:<i> In the last liberation  war, during our strategic</i>

292
00:12:56,475 --> 00:13:00,745
<i> retreat, the American hyenas  occupied the land of Sinchon.</i>

293
00:13:00,846 --> 00:13:02,648
<i> They arrested Min Youngshik</i>

294
00:13:03,014 --> 00:13:05,449
<i> and stabbed her muscles with a  three-pronged spear</i>

295
00:13:05,551 --> 00:13:07,018
<i> and sucked her flowing blood.</i>

296
00:13:07,451 --> 00:13:10,288
<i> They also took the flesh from  her thighs using a bayonet,</i>

297
00:13:10,489 --> 00:13:12,324
<i> dipped it in salt, and ate it.</i>

298
00:13:13,024 --> 00:13:15,427
And, in case you were wondering, yes, you can buy

299
00:13:15,527 --> 00:13:17,562
coasters depicting that scene in the museum gift shop,

300
00:13:17,663 --> 00:13:18,897
but they are 16 dollars,

301
00:13:18,996 --> 00:13:20,865
which is the real war crime there!

302
00:13:21,799 --> 00:13:24,269
And the North Koreans' indoctrination

303
00:13:24,369 --> 00:13:26,937
in anti-Americanism starts extremely young,

304
00:13:27,038 --> 00:13:28,340
as one defector remembers.

305
00:13:43,187 --> 00:13:44,689
-Holy shit! -(AUDIENCE GASPS)

306
00:13:44,789 --> 00:13:47,291
It is fascinating when a country's culture seeps

307
00:13:47,392 --> 00:13:48,961
even into their math lessons,

308
00:13:49,061 --> 00:13:50,095
although, it's not really surprising.

309
00:13:50,195 --> 00:13:52,197
As a British child, our math questions were,

310
00:13:52,297 --> 00:13:55,668
"If Johnny has two artifacts and Dinesh has two artifacts,

311
00:13:55,900 --> 00:13:58,503
then how many artifacts is Johnny about to have?

312
00:13:58,604 --> 00:14:02,307
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING) -The answer, of course, "All the artifacts."

313
00:14:02,740 --> 00:14:05,410
Dinesh's family can come visit them in the British museum

314
00:14:05,844 --> 00:14:07,245
whenever they're in town.

315
00:14:08,078 --> 00:14:11,516
And the notion that North Korea is working on a bomb that can,

316
00:14:11,616 --> 00:14:13,351
"Kill all the American bastards,"

317
00:14:13,451 --> 00:14:15,419
is a tremendous source of national pride,

318
00:14:15,687 --> 00:14:18,889
there have been stamps depicting missiles hurtling towards

319
00:14:18,990 --> 00:14:20,792
the U.S. Capitol, and a few years ago,

320
00:14:20,892 --> 00:14:23,495
they produced a video depicting the destruction of New York,

321
00:14:23,761 --> 00:14:26,463
set to the least appropriate song imaginable.

322
00:14:26,831 --> 00:14:29,000
(♪ WE ARE THE WORLD ♪ INSTRUMENTAL PLAYING)

323
00:14:41,245 --> 00:14:42,715
Yes, you heard right.

324
00:14:42,815 --> 00:14:45,483
That was a karaoke version of<i> "We are the World",</i>

325
00:14:45,582 --> 00:14:47,418
set to New York in flames.

326
00:14:47,952 --> 00:14:49,822
And the last time I saw a karaoke song

327
00:14:49,922 --> 00:14:52,291
with background imagery that inappropriate was

328
00:14:52,524 --> 00:14:54,958
every time I have ever sung karaoke.

329
00:14:55,058 --> 00:14:55,860
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

330
00:14:56,427 --> 00:14:58,395
I don't know what L.L. Cool J's<i>  "Doin' it"</i> has to do with

331
00:14:58,495 --> 00:15:00,298
these two babies in a field of sunflowers,

332
00:15:00,398 --> 00:15:02,734
but it's making everybody uncomfortable.

333
00:15:02,833 --> 00:15:03,834
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

334
00:15:04,369 --> 00:15:07,272
So, the North Korean regime has been very careful about

335
00:15:07,371 --> 00:15:10,607
presenting a threatening image of Americans to its people.

336
00:15:10,707 --> 00:15:13,745
And some activists have actually been trying to undermine that

337
00:15:14,011 --> 00:15:16,981
by sneaking information into the country on USB drives.

338
00:15:17,682 --> 00:15:19,084
(SPEAKING IN KOREAN)

339
00:15:19,283 --> 00:15:20,785
INTERPRETER:<i> We send  various content</i>

340
00:15:20,885 --> 00:15:23,254
<i> from stories on human rights,  general information on</i>

341
00:15:23,355 --> 00:15:26,390
<i>South Korea, to images depicting  the average American.</i>

342
00:15:26,791 --> 00:15:29,194
KARLA MURTHY: For<i> a fictional version  of the average American,</i>

343
00:15:29,293 --> 00:15:32,264
<i> TV shows like</i> The Mentalist,<i>  and</i> Desperate Housewives,

344
00:15:32,364 --> 00:15:35,133
<i> Kang says, scenes like  this one from</i> NCIS...

345
00:15:35,466 --> 00:15:38,502
Anything you say can and will be used against you in a court of law.

346
00:15:38,602 --> 00:15:40,471
MURTHY:<i> ...That show police  officers reading suspects</i>

347
00:15:40,572 --> 00:15:42,474
<i> their rights,  are especially useful.</i>

348
00:15:42,941 --> 00:15:45,610
You know what? If nothing else, we finally have our answer

349
00:15:45,711 --> 00:15:47,046
to the decade-long question,

350
00:15:47,145 --> 00:15:49,680
"Who the fuck is watching<i> NCIS?"</i>

351
00:15:49,780 --> 00:15:50,714
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

352
00:15:50,815 --> 00:15:53,018
It turns out, it's all your mom's friends

353
00:15:53,118 --> 00:15:54,753
and the people of North Korea.

354
00:15:55,486 --> 00:15:58,055
And if you think about it, that is very dangerous

355
00:15:58,157 --> 00:16:00,759
for Kim Jong-un, because if people get a sense

356
00:16:00,958 --> 00:16:03,227
that the image of America that he has carefully painted

357
00:16:03,327 --> 00:16:05,630
for them is false, he could have huge problems.

358
00:16:05,864 --> 00:16:07,766
And, when you understand him in that light,

359
00:16:07,865 --> 00:16:11,269
as a dictator desperately hedging against a loss of power,

360
00:16:11,369 --> 00:16:14,239
it is possible to understand why all his recent threats

361
00:16:14,339 --> 00:16:16,274
against the United States, have been reckless,

362
00:16:16,541 --> 00:16:18,610
but in his mind, also rational.

363
00:16:19,076 --> 00:16:21,312
And that brings us to the key question here,

364
00:16:21,413 --> 00:16:23,181
what are we going to do about this?

365
00:16:23,381 --> 00:16:25,282
Because on the campaign trail, Donald Trump

366
00:16:25,383 --> 00:16:26,718
made it all seem very simple.

367
00:16:27,217 --> 00:16:32,057
They said, "Would you speak to the leader of North Korea?"

368
00:16:32,857 --> 00:16:36,127
I said, "Absolutely. Why not? Why not?"

369
00:16:36,628 --> 00:16:39,764
And they come out, "Trump would speak to him!"

370
00:16:40,899 --> 00:16:43,567
Who the hell cares? I'll speak to anybody.

371
00:16:44,135 --> 00:16:46,236
-(AUDIENCE CHEERING FOR TRUMP) -Who knows?

372
00:16:46,471 --> 00:16:49,307
There's a ten percent or a 20 percent chance

373
00:16:50,075 --> 00:16:52,509
that I can talk him out of those damn nukes,

374
00:16:52,610 --> 00:16:54,779
'cause who the hell wants him to have nukes?

375
00:16:54,980 --> 00:16:56,413
And there's a chance!

376
00:16:56,880 --> 00:17:00,084
-No! No! There really isn't. -(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

377
00:17:00,184 --> 00:17:02,653
Partly because, remember, Kim Jong-un believes they are

378
00:17:02,754 --> 00:17:04,789
critical for his survival, and on top of that,

379
00:17:04,890 --> 00:17:07,492
Donald Trump is a shitty negotiator.

380
00:17:07,858 --> 00:17:10,162
In his short presidency, he has failed to get Mexico

381
00:17:10,261 --> 00:17:12,364
to pay for his stupid wall, he's failed to get

382
00:17:12,463 --> 00:17:15,700
a Congress his party controls to pass a health care bill,

383
00:17:15,799 --> 00:17:18,336
and even when his administration does get something done,

384
00:17:18,436 --> 00:17:21,071
it way oversells it, like when the White House

385
00:17:21,172 --> 00:17:23,173
announced a trade deal with China as,

386
00:17:23,273 --> 00:17:26,911
"Very Big News," "Gigantic," and "Herculean,"

387
00:17:27,011 --> 00:17:29,346
and one much-celebrated component turned out to be

388
00:17:29,446 --> 00:17:32,750
lifting a ban on beef imports that China had preliminarily

389
00:17:32,851 --> 00:17:34,553
agreed to last September.

390
00:17:34,653 --> 00:17:36,921
So way to fucking go there, Donald!

391
00:17:37,020 --> 00:17:39,191
What a very big, herculean deal!

392
00:17:39,290 --> 00:17:42,627
Thanks to you, except, not entirely thanks to you,

393
00:17:42,728 --> 00:17:46,631
America is now marginally more able to export beef again!

394
00:17:46,730 --> 00:17:47,665
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

395
00:17:47,766 --> 00:17:49,267
And since taking office,

396
00:17:49,366 --> 00:17:51,903
Trump has voiced support for an even simpler solution.

397
00:17:52,436 --> 00:17:55,206
China... is helping us

398
00:17:56,474 --> 00:17:58,609
possibly or probably,

399
00:17:58,810 --> 00:18:02,846
with the North Korean situation.

400
00:18:03,615 --> 00:18:05,616
-(AUDIENCE CHEERS) -Okay? Which is a great thing.

401
00:18:05,916 --> 00:18:06,717
Great thing.

402
00:18:07,352 --> 00:18:09,420
So, in the space of 14 seconds there,

403
00:18:09,520 --> 00:18:11,188
he said the word "great" twice,

404
00:18:11,423 --> 00:18:14,057
he pronounced "China" with three syllables,

405
00:18:14,291 --> 00:18:16,360
suggested someone else should do the work for him,

406
00:18:16,461 --> 00:18:18,462
and then, threw in a "possibly or probably,"

407
00:18:18,563 --> 00:18:19,932
rendering the whole thing meaningless.

408
00:18:20,031 --> 00:18:22,233
I think I may have just hit Trump bingo,

409
00:18:22,334 --> 00:18:24,869
and the prize that I want is to go drown in a river.

410
00:18:24,969 --> 00:18:25,903
(CROWD LAUGHS)

411
00:18:26,003 --> 00:18:29,707
But Trump's idea there of convincing China

412
00:18:29,807 --> 00:18:31,742
to exert influence on North Korea,

413
00:18:31,843 --> 00:18:33,545
is not inherently crazy.

414
00:18:33,744 --> 00:18:36,413
China shares an 800-mile border with North Korea

415
00:18:36,513 --> 00:18:38,282
and accounts for as much as 90 percent

416
00:18:38,383 --> 00:18:39,717
of North Korea's total trade,

417
00:18:39,817 --> 00:18:41,419
so they do have significant leverage.

418
00:18:41,519 --> 00:18:45,056
But, some are skeptical about just what China could,

419
00:18:45,155 --> 00:18:46,557
or is willing to do.

420
00:18:46,657 --> 00:18:49,760
Take sanctions. The U.N. have tried multiple rounds

421
00:18:49,861 --> 00:18:52,965
of increasingly-harsh sanctions, but North Korea has always found

422
00:18:53,065 --> 00:18:54,166
easy ways around them.

423
00:18:54,665 --> 00:18:56,033
(SPEAKING KOREAN)

424
00:18:56,134 --> 00:18:58,736
INTERPRETER:<i> North Korea is a  100% state enterprise,</i>

425
00:18:59,002 --> 00:19:01,204
<i> so these companies change  their names the next day</i>

426
00:19:01,306 --> 00:19:02,640
<i>if they're listed for sanctions.</i>

427
00:19:03,040 --> 00:19:05,710
<i> That way the company stays,  but with different names</i>

428
00:19:05,810 --> 00:19:07,311
<i> whenever there are sanctions.</i>

429
00:19:07,412 --> 00:19:10,649
<i> If I'm included in the list,  my name can be changed, too.</i>

430
00:19:11,115 --> 00:19:13,984
Yeah, and that is some pretty weak enforcement.

431
00:19:14,251 --> 00:19:15,019
Think about it this way,

432
00:19:15,486 --> 00:19:17,923
let's say HBO decided they wanted to cancel this show,

433
00:19:18,022 --> 00:19:20,924
their hand would be pretty weak if I was able to get around that

434
00:19:21,025 --> 00:19:22,460
simply by changing the name to

435
00:19:22,559 --> 00:19:25,763
<i> "Earlier Times but Now Starring Spance Mörgendörffer."</i>

436
00:19:25,864 --> 00:19:26,965
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS, APPLAUDS)

437
00:19:27,065 --> 00:19:29,834
And it is true that China could increase

438
00:19:29,933 --> 00:19:32,503
enforcement of its sanctions, but they are understandably

439
00:19:32,604 --> 00:19:34,439
worried about where that could lead.

440
00:19:35,073 --> 00:19:37,175
What they worry about is, if they do that,

441
00:19:37,275 --> 00:19:38,676
will the regime collapse?

442
00:19:39,109 --> 00:19:41,245
What does that mean? Millions of refugees

443
00:19:41,346 --> 00:19:44,682
pouring into China, uh, possibly a unified Korea,

444
00:19:44,782 --> 00:19:46,650
that is then a Pro-American country

445
00:19:46,851 --> 00:19:48,587
sitting on their southern border where, don't forget,

446
00:19:48,686 --> 00:19:51,455
there are 30,000 American troops in South Korea,

447
00:19:51,556 --> 00:19:53,191
which would then be on China's border,

448
00:19:53,290 --> 00:19:55,192
and by the way, 15 nuclear weapons.

449
00:19:55,726 --> 00:19:58,530
You know that there are a lot of problems when you end up

450
00:19:58,630 --> 00:20:01,599
saying, "Oh, and by the way, 15 nuclear weapons."

451
00:20:02,032 --> 00:20:04,135
Imagine you were a babysitter and you heard,

452
00:20:04,236 --> 00:20:06,705
"Okay, you've got his EpiPen, you know about his nut allergy,

453
00:20:06,805 --> 00:20:09,039
he needs his inhaler every hour, oh, and by the way,

454
00:20:09,140 --> 00:20:10,908
he has 15 nuclear weapons."

455
00:20:11,008 --> 00:20:12,175
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

456
00:20:12,276 --> 00:20:14,812
Now Trump has also been mentioning military solutions,

457
00:20:14,912 --> 00:20:17,682
but even targeted strikes against weapons systems

458
00:20:17,781 --> 00:20:19,917
could get out of hand very fast.

459
00:20:20,218 --> 00:20:22,086
North Korea would likely retaliate and they have

460
00:20:22,186 --> 00:20:25,656
an estimated 8,000 pieces of heavy artillery stationed

461
00:20:25,757 --> 00:20:28,226
just north of the DMZ, which is here.

462
00:20:28,492 --> 00:20:30,729
And that artillery is capable of reaching Seoul,

463
00:20:30,828 --> 00:20:32,396
which is just 40 miles away,

464
00:20:32,497 --> 00:20:35,166
and is an area with 25 million people.

465
00:20:35,266 --> 00:20:39,071
So, even a non-nuclear war could have horrific results.

466
00:20:39,270 --> 00:20:41,772
And, let's just engage in some truly magical thinking.

467
00:20:41,873 --> 00:20:44,976
What if you could somehow just take out Kim Jong-un?

468
00:20:45,277 --> 00:20:48,313
Well, you've probably got an immediate humanitarian crisis

469
00:20:48,413 --> 00:20:50,414
on your hands, as well as a leaderless country

470
00:20:50,515 --> 00:20:52,682
with a power vacuum and nuclear weapons.

471
00:20:52,950 --> 00:20:55,120
And, as we've learned from Iraq and Afghanistan,

472
00:20:55,220 --> 00:20:57,588
when regimes fall and there's no plan in place,

473
00:20:57,689 --> 00:21:00,191
that vacuum can be filled with terrible things.

474
00:21:00,525 --> 00:21:04,629
We do not want to find out what North Korea's ISIS would be.

475
00:21:04,962 --> 00:21:07,731
Even just the phrase, "North Korea's ISIS"

476
00:21:07,832 --> 00:21:09,567
is absolutely terrifying.

477
00:21:09,933 --> 00:21:12,302
It's like saying, "9/11's Bill Cosby."

478
00:21:12,502 --> 00:21:16,707
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHING) -What would that even be? I hope we never have to find out.

479
00:21:17,642 --> 00:21:21,011
So, sanctions are no guarantee and military action could be

480
00:21:21,112 --> 00:21:23,815
catastrophic and diplomacy is going to be extremely difficult,

481
00:21:23,914 --> 00:21:27,085
given that you usually need to have a specific goal in mind,

482
00:21:27,184 --> 00:21:30,254
and Trump seems to be making all of this up as he goes along.

483
00:21:30,888 --> 00:21:32,789
We are learning stunning new details about

484
00:21:32,890 --> 00:21:35,894
President Trump's extraordinary "fire and fury" threat tonight,

485
00:21:36,126 --> 00:21:38,696
multiple sources telling CNN the president ad-libbed

486
00:21:38,797 --> 00:21:41,298
those words, they were improvised, on the fly.

487
00:21:41,833 --> 00:21:45,803
For fuck's sake! That is just not a good idea.

488
00:21:45,903 --> 00:21:49,941
As I'm sure someone has had to say to Wayne Brady at a funeral more than once,

489
00:21:50,241 --> 00:21:52,943
"Now is not a good time to improvise."

